post_cb({"6281715": {"PostTypeId": "2", "ParentId": "6281472", "Body": "<p>Section 5.1.2 paragraph 5 specifically says that you can not have default values for the parameters.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_6281472_6281715_0\">Default arguments (8.3.6) shall not be specified in the <em>parameter-declaration-clause</em> of a <em>lambda-declarator</em>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "CreationDate": "2011-06-08T15:57:33.000", "Score": "14", "CommentCount": "7", "Id": "6281715", "OwnerUserId": "597607", "LastActivityDate": "2011-06-08T15:57:33.000"}, "6282643": {"PostTypeId": "2", "ParentId": "6281472", "Body": "<p>It makes no sense to have a default argument in a lambda function -- how could it ever be used? On the other hand, it does no harm, so why not allow it, after emitting a warning?</p>\n", "CreationDate": "2011-06-08T17:16:35.833", "Score": "2", "CommentCount": "7", "Id": "6282643", "OwnerUserId": "428857", "LastActivityDate": "2011-06-08T17:16:35.833"}, "6281472": {"LastEditDate": "2011-06-08T17:50:59.297", "Body": "<p>I had this lambda somewhere in my code:</p>\n<pre><code>[](bool a, bool=true){ return !a;} }\n</code></pre>\n<p>and GCC 4.6 \"complained\" with this warning:</p>\n<pre><code>warning: default argument specified for lambda parameter [-pedantic]\n</code></pre>\n<p>Which is mightily unhelpful when you don't know why this is \"bad\". I consulted the FDIS n3290 and didn't find anything in <code>5.1.2 Lambda Expressions</code> with regards to default arguments and a lambda.</p>\n<p><strike><strong>UPDATE:</strong> I filed a bug report <a href=\"http://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=49326\">here</a>.</strike></p>\n<p><strong>UPDATE2:</strong> OK, from now on I'm using <code>-pedantic-errors</code>. <code>-pedantic</code> only emits warnings, not errors.</p>\n", "CreationDate": "2011-06-08T15:39:53.770", "Score": "16", "AcceptedAnswerId": "6281715", "CommentCount": "9", "OwnerUserId": "256138", "Title": "Why does a default argument for a lambda argument trigger a -pedantic\" GCC warning?", "LastActivityDate": "2016-03-06T19:37:27.487", "PostTypeId": "1", "Tags": "<c++><lambda><c++11>", "AnswerCount": "3", "FavoriteCount": "3", "Id": "6281472", "ViewCount": "3754", "LastEditorUserId": "256138"}, "35831564": {"PostTypeId": "2", "ParentId": "6281472", "Body": "<p>Since C++14 <a href=\"http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/lambda\">it is allowed</a>. It was found to be a defect long time ago: <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/cwg_defects.html#974\">Default arguments for lambdas</a>, and also <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/cwg_defects.html#1814\">Default arguments in lambda-expressions</a>. </p>\n", "CreationDate": "2016-03-06T19:37:27.487", "Score": "7", "CommentCount": "0", "Id": "35831564", "OwnerUserId": "471160", "LastActivityDate": "2016-03-06T19:37:27.487"}, "bq_ids": {"n3337": {"so_6281472_6281715_0": {"quality": 0.8333333333333334, "length": 5, "section_id": 5733}}}});